Insights on human dataset

Linear Regression Analysis

Introduction

This part of my final assignment will focus on analysing a data set named humanW, it originates from the United Nations Development Programme. See their data page for more information. For a nice overview see also the calculating the human development indices pdf. Most of the variable names in the data have been shortened and two new variables have been computed. See the meta file. For the modified data please check our renamed variables and wrangled raw data, as well as R script for data wrangling.

Briefly, the data combines several indicators from most countries in the world that can be broadly classified into those related to Health and knowledge and others related to Empowerment.

Research Question

Is the Gross National Income per Capita (GNI) as predicted with other development indices in African nations compared with Non-African nations?

pW

From the previous plot we can notice that African nations comprise about 23% of studied countries; nevertheless, they cause considerable heterogenity in data in almost all parameters except for the Percetange of female representatives in parliament which is surprisingly almost similar to other non-African countries.

Clear difference can be captured in African nations regarding less female to male ratio with secondary education, less expected years of schooling, less life expectance at birth, less than average GNI which is less normally distributed and higher yet more normally distributed Maternal mortality rates and Adolesence birth rates.

So, I have got the taste that in Africa the condition is unique.

Fitting regression model

for African countries

A multiple linear regression model with four explanatory variables (Edu2.FM, Labo.FM, Mat.Mor and Edu.Exp) selected based on the preliminary inspection of the dataset is fitted to investigate the relationship between them and the dependent outcome variable GNI.

#First model with four explanatory variables in African
mod<-lm(GNI~Edu2.FM+Labo.FM+Mat.Mor+Edu.Exp,data=human_Africa)
summary(mod)

The summary report of the fitted model shows that Edu2.FM has a positive impact on GNI. Interestingly, the Labo.FM has considerable negative impact on GNI and Edu.Exp has a positive impact but less than Edu2.FM, estimates for Mat.Mor prove to be non-signicifant.

Now, what if we exclude Mat.Mor from our model?

in our final model the three explanatory variables are significantly affecting GNI with highest for Edu2FM.(positively) and Labo.FM(negatively), and lower with Edu.Exp(positively). Explanatory power of the final model has Adjusted R-squared of 0.701 a little bit better than the first one (0.695) indicating that the model predicts appoximately 70% of the variation in GNI.

The final model has the potential to explain about 86% of variation in GNI based on two explanatory variables of Labo.FM (with quite high significant negative correlation) and Edu.Exp (with a high significant positive correlation), we found that the model was enhanced after exclusion of extreme influential observations whereas it was not improved after trying to exckude Libya which proved to be less influential and its removal made thw fit worse; thus kept in.

Conclusion

The Edu.Exp (Expected years of schooling) is a significant positive predictor for GNI in both African and non-African countries, however, ratio of females/males in the labour force is very significantly correlated as a negative predictor of GNI only in African countries, this means that the higher ratio of females in labour force is mostly related to lower levels of GNI.

My personal interpretation for such result could be that lower economic status is a strong drive for females’ working in African countries and not in other non-African countries, or may be that females in African countries should be addressed with development programs to improve their impact on their countries’ national income.

Odds, odds ratio and confidence intervals

An odds ratio (OR) is a measure of association between an exposure and an outcome. The OR represents the odds that an outcome will occur given a particular exposure, compared to the odds of the outcome occurring in the absence of that exposure. See Explaining odds Ratios

When a logistic regression is calculated, the regression coefficient is the estimated increase in the log odds of the outcome per unit increase in the value of the exposure. In other words, the exponential function of the regression coefficient is the odds ratio associated with a one-unit increase in the exposure.

# let's see our regression coefficient and its exponential as well as confidence intervals (CI)
coef(m1)
## (Intercept)     Labo.FM 
##         2.9        -5.1
OR <- coef(m1) %>% exp()

CI <- confint(m1) %>% exp()
cbind(OR, CI)
##                  OR    2.5 % 97.5 %
## (Intercept) 17.6257 1.539213 358.43
## Labo.FM      0.0059 0.000098   0.16

As expected our confidence interval did not include one and is totally to the left in the negative correlation side. Based on previous summery we can expect very large increase (5 times) in odds of being a country with less than medium GNI for only minimal unit increase in ratio of females to males in the labour force in African nations.

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {

  mean(n_wrong)

Cross validation and optimization

Cross-validation tests the model on unseen data, performing cross-validation on our model.

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)

cv$delta[1]

mbetter<-glm(GNIcat2~Labo.FM+Edu.Exp,family=binomial,data=human_Africacat_)

the inclusion of the variable Edu.Exp dramatically improved the model and decreased the percentage of misclassified observations significantly, I am not surprised as this goes in accordance with our initial linear regression results discussed earlier.

Linear discriminant analysis

Introduction

Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher’s linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events. The resulting combination may be used as a linear classifier, or, more commonly, for dimensionality reduction before later classification.

Here, we will continue analysind data concerning African countries with regard to their GNI.

LDA (bi)plots

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 0.8, arrow_heads = 0.08, color = "deeppink", tex = 0.95, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

As expected in this final model it was found that the three basic variables that contribute to the explaining of almost 99% of the variation in GNI are in order of impact Labo.FM with negative direction, Edu.Exp followed by Edu2.FM in the positive direction.

K-means

Introduction

k-means clustering aims to partition n observations into k clusters in which each observation belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean, serving as a prototype of the cluster. This results in a partitioning of the data space into Voronoi cells.

Eclidean and Manhattan distances

We will operate on African_scaled2 data and examine the distance properties of the data and compare methods in both the Euclidian (geometric) and Manhattan (along the axes) distance.

African_scaled2 <- scale(human_AfricaLDA) %>% as.data.frame()
class(African_scaled2)
## [1] "data.frame"
#Euclidean distance matrix
dist_eu<-dist(African_scaled2)
#for comparison Manhattan distance matrix
dist_man<-dist(African_scaled2,method = "manhattan" )
#summaries 
summary(dist_eu)#Euclidian
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     1.1     2.7     3.6     3.7     4.7     8.0
summary(dist_man)#Manhattan
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     2.1     6.0     8.3     8.9    11.3    20.8

Preliminary K-means and determination of the optimal number of clusters

K-means algorith is exploratorily ran on the dataset using 5 clusters.

#kmeans using euclidean and five clusters
km <- kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 5)
pairs(African_scaled2, col = km$cluster,lower.panel = NULL)

Now, let’s assess what is the optimal number of clusters and run the algorithm again.

k_max <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(dist_eu, k)$tot.withinss})
#Plot the results
plot(1:k_max, twcss, type = 'b')

So, the plot shows that optimally we would have 2 clusters as the most prominent change in the sum of squares happens at 2.

K-means using the optimal number of clusters

km <- kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 2)
pairs(African_scaled2, col = km$cluster, lower.panel = NULL)

The scatter plot with only two clusters shows all data points are assigned to two red/black clusters. The clearer separation for the colours the more relevant for clustering the variable. GNI and Labo.FM seem to discriminate quite well between the two clusters.

LDA fitting to K-means

This will be performed by K-means on the scaled data using 4 clusters. Therafter, LDA is fitted using the generated clusters as target classes.

set.seed(123)

African_scaled4 <- as.data.frame(scale(human_AfricaLDA,center=TRUE,scale = TRUE))
dist_eu4 <- dist(African_scaled4)
km2 <-kmeans(dist_eu4, centers = 4)
African_scaled4$classes<-km2$cluster
lda.fit3 <- lda(African_scaled4$classes ~., data = African_scaled4)
lda.arrows3 <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
plot(lda.fit3, dimen = 2, col= as.numeric(African_scaled4$classes), pch=classes)
lda.arrows3(lda.fit3, myscale = 1)

Again, four clusters separated and we can taste the opposite dirction of GNI with Labo.FM in African countries.

To enable the method the data set should be fine-tuned by scaling the mean of every variable to zero by ubtracting the column means from the corresponding columns and dividing the difference with standard deviation.

Conclusion

This model prediction is good for low and high GNI categories based on the variables of life.Exp, Edu.Exp, Mat.Mor and (negatively) Ado.Birth as the major discriminants, however, for med_low and med_high it’s not as accurate.

Summary

There is clear difference in the correlation and impact of variables between African countries and non-African countries. Such difference should be assessed as well among different continents, and it throughs the light on different cultural and social factors that confounds with observations and that should be approached with care before drawing any generalized conclusions based on heterogenous backgrounds. Taking into consideration those differences yet increases our understanding of human behavior in communities around the world; allowing us improve and enhance human development.
